This album completely went over Anthony's head. Every moment of this album is filled with intent and purpose. Do you really think Donald Glover would wait so long to release this under his own name and have it be half assed? Unsubscribed.

This album is revolutionary. The first time I heard it with my girlfriend (HEADPHONES REQUIRED!) the first thing we did was listen to it again because we were so awestruck.

Donald Glover completely subverts any expectations of what music should be, in the same way artists like NMesh and Macintosh Plus do, except with original sounds and synths and no samples. This is an experience, not a collection of tracks like we're used to.

snippet.textDisplay:
I really don’t know too many people who are middle ground with Donald Glover/childish gambino. From everyone I’ve talked to, it seems people either love him and think he’s an absolute musical genius who is paving the way for future music and showcasing his elaborate and diverse musical (amongst others) talent... or they think he’s an overrated, underwhelming, unappealing musical figure whose position within the industry just does not seem apparent, nor does it make any sense. I personally absolutely love gambino. I’ve been listening since I was in 5th grade and I’m a junior in high school now. I’ve grown up loving all of his music and have recently been in search for some of his hidden gems, such as ‘Melrose’ and ‘What Kind of Love’... But at this point in time it almost feels like he has lost his footing and has become more concerned with showcasing his ability to produce [insert subjective and opinionated adjective to describe music here] music in genres of rap, funk, soul, hip hop, and more, rather than just settling for one. Yet at the same time Donald Glover is evidently not the kind of man to settle with what he knows will appeal to pop culture. He’s trying new things out, pushing boundaries, experimenting. He’s already dipped into enormous success and in my opinion doesn’t owe it to anyone to prove himself in the rap or hip hop industry anymore. Because The Internet was absolutely fucking fantastic. Awaken my Love was unrefutably ahead of its time. And even though I can honestly only say I enjoy 4 or 5 songs on the album, and I only really enjoy 1 or 2, I by no means think that this attempt by Donald Glover was a failure.

At this point Donald is just contributing to the progression of the human experimentation with sound. I no longer believe he’s in the industry to compete.

This was one of my most anticipated albums as well especially because if I remember correctly this was announced to be the last Childish Gambino album way back.
The entire weird release gimmick and the strange song titles confused the fuck out of me and the album sounded very unlike Childish Gambino and the tracks disconnected from each other. But after a bunch of listens I have to say I like half of the album quite a lot. The first half especially. I got a good handful of tracks I really like to vibe to even when there are others I completely hate. 35.32 is fucking terrible for example. But 12.38, 19.10 and 47.48 are a lot of fun to listen to for me.

I think this is the FIRST of 4 albums.

Donald released two vital pieces of work with the album. A note and a piece of concept art. In the note, he referred to this project as the "First Book" and the cover art had 4 individual covers.


That's why it took him four years to release the music and why many other songs (Human Sacrifice, Saturday, This Is America, Summertime Magic, etc.) weren't on this album; but "Feels Like Summer" was.
